How can the Paladin class be optimized for group support and healing during combat, while still maintaining its offensive capabilities?

Here is a character build for a D&D 5e Paladin specialized in supporting and healing their allies, without sacrificing their damage-dealing abilities:

Attributes:
- Strength: 16
- Dexterity: 10
- Constitution: 14
- Intelligence: 10
- Wisdom: 14
- Charisma: 16

Feats:
1st level: Healer
2nd level: Protection Fighting Style
4th level: Aura of Vitality
6th level: Sentinel
8th level: Cleansing Touch
10th level: Holy Weapon

Here is a Java code example related to the above content:

public class Paladin {
    private int strength;
    private int dexterity;
    private int constitution;
    private int intelligence;
    private int wisdom;
    private int charisma;

    public Paladin(int strength, int dexterity, int constitution, int intelligence, int wisdom, int charisma) {
        this.strength = strength;
        this.dexterity = dexterity;
        this.constitution = constitution;
        this.intelligence = intelligence;
        this.wisdom = wisdom;
        this.charisma = charisma;
    }

    public int getStrength() {
        return strength;
    }

    public int getDexterity() {
        return dexterity;
    }

    public int getConstitution() {
        return constitution;
    }

    public int getIntelligence() {
        return intelligence;
    }

    public int getWisdom() {
        return wisdom;
    }

    public int getCharisma() {
        return charisma;
    }

    public void healAlly(Player target) {
        System.out.println("Paladin healed " + target.getName() + " with Aura of Vitality!");
    }

    public void buffGroup() {
        System.out.println("Paladin provided protection and support to their allies with Holy Weapon!");
    }

    public void cleanseAllies() {
        System.out.println("Paladin cleansed their allies of any negative effects with Cleansing Touch!");
    }
}

public class Player {
    private String name;
    private int maxHp;
    private int currentHp;

    public Player(String name, int maxHp) {
        this.name = name;
        this.maxHp = maxHp;
        this.currentHp = maxHp;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public int getMaxHp() {
        return maxHp;
    }

    public int getCurrentHp() {
        return currentHp;
    }

    public void setCurrentHp(int currentHp) {
        this.currentHp = currentHp;
    }
}

public class Game {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Player paladin = new Player("Paladin", 60);
        Player ally1 = new Player("Ally1", 50);
        Player ally2 = new Player("Ally2", 40);

        Paladin myPaladin = new Paladin(16, 10, 14, 10, 14, 16);

        myPaladin.healAlly(ally1);
        myPaladin.buffGroup();
        myPaladin.cleanseAllies();
    }
}

### Response:
This code example demonstrates a basic implementation of a Paladin class and its abilities in a D&D-like game. The Paladin class has attributes for strength, dexterity, constitution, intelligence, wisdom, and charisma. The Paladin class also has methods for healing an ally with Aura of Vitality, buffing the group with Holy Weapon, and cleansing allies of negative effects with Cleansing Touch. 

The Player class represents individual characters in the game and has attributes for name, maximum hit points, and current hit points. The Game class uses instances of the Player and Paladin classes to simulate game scenarios. 

Overall, this code example provides a foundation for creating a more advanced Paladin class with additional abilities and tactics for group support and healing while still maintaining its offensive capabilities.

